{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"333a2b06-2912-4183-8f61-19bdcaaf2e97","content":"## Analysis: `ResolveProjectReferences` is a red herring\n\n**It's not a real bottleneck.** Here's why:\n\n`ResolveProjectReferences` is the MSBuild target that *triggers the build of your referenced projects*. When you see it consuming ~70% of build time, that number **includes the entire compilation of LibA and LibB** — it's an accounting artifact in the binlog, not a separate expensive operation.\n\nYour dependency graph is:\n```\nApp → LibA\nApp → LibB → LibA\n```\n\nThe time is spent *compiling those libraries*, not \"resolving\" anything.\n\n### Why the proposed fixes are wrong:\n\n| Idea | Problem |\n|------|---------|\n| Replace with NuGet packages | Kills inner-loop dev speed; you still pay compile cost somewhere |\n| Skip/override the target | Breaks the build — referenced assemblies won't exist |\n| Merge into one project | Sacrifices modularity for zero real gain |\n\n### What to actually optimize:\n\n1. **Check incremental builds** — if LibA/LibB rebuild when unchanged, fix that (`dotnet build` should no-op). Run `dotnet build` twice; the second should be near-instant.\n2. **Use graph-based builds** — `dotnet build --graph` enables better parallelism across projects.\n3. **Look at the real expensive target** — open the binlog and look at `CoreCompile` time *within* the referenced projects. That's where actual seconds are spent.\n\n**Bottom line:** With only 2 small class libraries, your build is already fast. The 70% figure is misleading because the total time is tiny — optimizing here would yield milliseconds at best.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"aba5215b-fcea-417c-93aa-8ca06a84cbad","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a good picture. Let me analyze this:\n\n1. The project structure is: App → LibA, App → LibB → LibA\n2. There are only 2 project references from App, and LibB has 1 reference to LibA.\n3. This is a tiny project - trivial class libraries.\n\nThe key insight: `ResolveProjectReferences` showing as ~70% of build time is **misleading**. Here's why:\n\n- `ResolveProjectReferences` is the target that triggers the build of referenced projects (LibA, LibB). It's not just \"resolving\" references — it's actually building the dependency projects.\n\n\n- In MSBuild's Target Performance Summary, this target gets blamed for all the time spent building the referenced projects because that's the target that invoked those builds — it's an accounting artifact of how the binlog attributes work.\n- With only 2 tiny libraries, there's essentially nothing to optimize here. The \"70%\" is high because the overall build time is so small that the overhead of resolving and building 2 trivial projects dominates relative to everything else.\n- The proposed solutions don't actually help: NuGet packages add complexity and slow development, skipping the target breaks the build, and consolidating sacrifices modularity for no real gain. If they want faster builds, they should focus on whether the referenced projects are being rebuilt unnecessarily or use `dotnet build --graph` for better parallelism.","outputTokens":858,"requestId":"F018:1A905D:12BCF41:1527789:69F942C7"},"id":"f701150d-91ca-40b4-9ca2-396232711db8","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:07:38.783Z","parentId":"b6ecb8a8-cfa4-45f7-9084-ac9fd6c90b42"}
